<section xml:id="section-absolute-value-and-square-root">

    <title>Absolute Value and Square Root</title>

    <introduction>
    	<p>In this section, we will learn the basics of absolute value and square root, two concepts frequently used in later lessons. We will start with video lectures.</p>

    	 <figure>
        	<caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        	<video youtube="L8fGfc7Wcco" width="70%"/>
        	<video youtube="Ymcf14wC9Ck" width="70%"/>
    	</figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Introdcution to Absolute Value</title>

        <definition xml:id="definition-absolute-value">
            <notation>
                <usage>\abs{x}</usage>
                <description>absolute value</description>
            </notation>
            <statement>
                <p>The <term>absolute value</term> of a number is the distance between <m>0</m> and that number on the number line. For the absolute value of <m>x</m>, we write <m>\abs{x}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>Let's look at the absolute value of <m>2</m> and <m>-2</m>.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption><m>\abs{2}</m> and <m>\abs{-2}</m></caption>
            <image width="70%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
						\draw [<->, color=black] (-4,0) -- (4,0);
						\foreach \x in {-3,-2,...,3}
			    			\draw (\x,-1pt) -- (\x,1pt);
						\foreach \x in {-3,-2,...,3}
			    			\node [below] at (\x,0) {\x};
			    		\draw [-] (0,0.5) -- (0,1);
			    		\draw [-] (2,0.5) -- (2,1);
			    		\draw [-] (-2,0.5) -- (-2,1);
			    		\draw [<->] (0,0.75) -- (2,0.75);
			    		\draw [<->] (0,0.75) -- (-2,0.75);
			    		\node at (1,1) {$\mid2\mid=2$};
			    		\node at (-1,1) {$\mid-2\mid=2$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p>Since the distance between <m>2</m> and <m>0</m> on the number line is <m>2</m> units, the absolute value of <m>2</m> is <m>2</m>. We write <m>\abs{2}=2</m>.</p>

        <p>Since the distance between <m>-2</m> and <m>0</m> on the number line is also <m>2</m> units, the absolute value of <m>-2</m> is also <m>2</m>. We write <m>\abs{-2}=2</m>.</p>

        <p>In summary, absolute value can remove a negative number's negative sign, but it doesn't change the value of a positive number.</p>

        <example>
        	<statement>
	        	<p>Evalue the following expressions:<md>
	        		<mrow>\abs{-5}\amp=<fillin/></mrow>
	        		<mrow>\abs{1-2}\amp=<fillin/></mrow>
	        		<mrow>-\abs{-5}\amp=<fillin/></mrow>
	        	</md></p>
        	</statement>
        	<solution>
	        	<p><md>
	        		<mrow>\abs{-5}\amp=5</mrow>
	        		<mrow>\abs{1-2}\amp=\abs{-1}=1</mrow>
	        		<mrow>-\abs{-5}\amp=-5</mrow>
	        	</md></p>

	        	<p>For the second problem, we may not do: <m>\abs{1-2}=\abs{1}+\abs{2}</m>. We have to complete calculation inside the absolute value symbols before applying the absolute value.</p>

	        	<p>For the third problem, the absolute value cannot remove the negative sign <em>outside</em> the absolute symbols.</p>
        	</solution>
        </example>

