	        </exercise>
        </exercise>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Square Root Facts</title>

    	<p>It would be very helpful if you can memorize the first few perfect square numbers:<md>
    		<mrow>0^2\amp=0</mrow>
    		<mrow>1^2\amp=1</mrow>
    		<mrow>2^2\amp=4</mrow>
    		<mrow>3^2\amp=9</mrow>
    		<mrow>4^2\amp=16</mrow>
    		<mrow>5^2\amp=25</mrow>
    		<mrow>6^2\amp=36</mrow>
    		<mrow>7^2\amp=49</mrow>
    		<mrow>8^2\amp=64</mrow>
    		<mrow>9^2\amp=81</mrow>
    		<mrow>10^2\amp=100</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    	<p>Square root is the opposite operation of square. For example, since <m>3^2=9</m>, the square root of <m>9</m> is <m>3</m>. Square root of <m>9</m> is looking for a positive number whose square is <m>9</m>.</p>

        <definition xml:id="definition-square-root">
            <notation>
                <usage>\sqrt{x}</usage>
                <description>square root</description>
            </notation>
            <statement>
                <p>The <term>square root</term> of <m>x</m> is a positive number <m>y</m> such that <m>y^2=x</m>. We write <m>\sqrt{x}=y</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>The following facts should be memorized:<md>
        	<mrow>0^2\amp=0\amp\sqrt{0}=0</mrow>
        	<mrow>1^2\amp=1\amp\sqrt{1}=1</mrow>
    		<mrow>2^2\amp=4\amp\sqrt{4}=2</mrow>
    		<mrow>3^2\amp=9\amp\sqrt{9}=3</mrow>
    		<mrow>4^2\amp=16\amp\sqrt{16}=4</mrow>
    		<mrow>5^2\amp=25\amp\sqrt{25}=5</mrow>
    		<mrow>6^2\amp=36\amp\sqrt{36}=6</mrow>
    		<mrow>7^2\amp=49\amp\sqrt{49}=7</mrow>
    		<mrow>8^2\amp=64\amp\sqrt{64}=8</mrow>
    		<mrow>9^2\amp=81\amp\sqrt{81}=9</mrow>
    		<mrow>10^2\amp=100\amp\sqrt{100}=10</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    	<p>We should also be able to calculate related facts, such as<md>
        	<mrow>0.1^2\amp=0.01\amp\sqrt{0.01}=0.1</mrow>
        	<mrow>0.2^2\amp=0.04\amp\sqrt{0.04}=0.2</mrow>
    		<mrow>30^2\amp=900\amp\sqrt{900}=30</mrow>
    		<mrow>100^2\amp=10,000\amp\sqrt{10,000}=100</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Calculating Square Root with Calculator</title>

    	<p>Most square root numbers are actually decimals. Take <m>\sqrt{5}</m> as an example:<md>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{4}\amp=2</mrow>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{5}\amp=?</mrow>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{9}\amp=3</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    	<p>Since <m>5</m> is between <m>4</m> and <m>9</m>, the square root of <m>5</m> must be between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>. Because <m>5</m> is closer to <m>4</m> than <m>9</m>, the square root of <m>5</m> must be closer to <m>2</m> than <m>3</m>. With a calculator, we can see<me>\sqrt{5}=2.236...</me>Actually the decimal will not terminate. With a calculator, we can verify that<me>2.236^2=4.999...</me>If we use a more accurate value than <m>2.236</m>, its square will be closer to <m>5</m>.</p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Square Root of Fractions</title>

    	<p>We should be able to calculate the square root of some fractions, such as<md>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{\frac{1}{4}}\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{\frac{4}{9}}\amp=\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{\frac{9}{4}}\amp=\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Square Root of Negative Numbers</title>

    	<p>Can we find the square root of negative numbers, such as <m>\sqrt{-1}</m>? Assume <m>\sqrt{-1}=x</m>, and let's try to find <m>x</m>:<md>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{9}=3 \text{ because } 3^2=9</mrow>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{-1}=x \text{ because } x^2=-1</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    	<p>Which number's square is <m>-1</m>? Nothing! It's not <m>-1</m> because <m>(-1)^2=1</m>. Since no number's square is <m>-1</m>, we say the square root of <m>-1</m> (actually the square root of all negative numbers) is <term>undefined</term>.</p>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
    	<title>Square Root Operations</title>

    	<p>Here is a very common mistake we must avoid:<me>\sqrt{9+16}=\sqrt{9}+\sqrt{16}</me>This is wrong because <m>\sqrt{9+16}=\sqrt{25}=5</m>, but <m>\sqrt{9}+\sqrt{16}=3+4=7</m>. When there is addition or subtraction inside a square root, we may not break one square root into two. Instead, we must complete the inside operations first, and then apply the square root. For example,<me>\sqrt{100-64}=\sqrt{36}=6</me></p>

    	<p>When the inside operation is multiplication or division, we could actually break one square root into two. For example:<md>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{4\cdot9}=\sqrt{36}=6</mrow>
    		<mrow>\sqrt{4\cdot9}=\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{9}=2\cdot3=6</mrow>
    	</md></p>

    	<p>When we learned how to find the square root of a fraction, we actually broke one square root into two. For example:<me>\sqrt{\frac{4}{9}}=\frac{\sqrt{4}}{\sqrt{9}}=\frac{2}{3}</me></p>

    	<p>Let's summarize what we learned into a theorem.</p>

		<theorem xml:id="theorem-square-root-property">
            <title>Properties of Square Root</title>
            <index><main>Properties of Square Root</main></index>
            <statement><p><md>
                <mrow>\sqrt{x+y}\amp\ne\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{y}</mrow>
                <mrow>\sqrt{x-y}\amp\ne\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{y}</mrow>
                <mrow>\sqrt{x\cdot y}\amp=\sqrt{x}\cdot\sqrt{y}</mrow>
                <mrow>\sqrt{\frac{x}{y}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt{x}}{\sqrt{y}}, \text{ where }y\ne0</mrow>
            </md></p></statement>
        </theorem>

        <p>This is not the first time a property works for multiplication/division, but not for addition/subtraction. The rules are very similar when we reduce fractions:<md>
        	<mrow>\frac{2}{4}\amp=\frac{\cancel{2}\cdot1}{\cancel{2}\cdot2}=\frac{1}{2}\amp\text{we can do this}</mrow>
        	<mrow>\frac{3}{4}\amp=\frac{\cancel{2}+1}{\cancel{2}+2}\ne\frac{1}{2}\amp\text{we cannot do this}</mrow>
        </md></p>

    </subsection>

